---
import { withBase } from '../lib/url';
import Prose from '../layouts/Prose.astro';
import Quote from '../components/Quote.astro';
import ShieldChart from '../components/ShieldChart.astro';
import HouseChart from '../components/HouseChart.astro';
---

<Prose
  title="How to Cast a Geomantic Chart"
  description="Casting the geomantic chart step by step: the sixteen lines, the four Mothers, Daughters, Nieces, Witnesses and Judge, and the shield chart, as the historical sources teach it."
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Casting' }]}
  kicker="Practice"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: 'How to Cast a Geomantic Chart' }]}
>
  <p>
    A geomantic reading begins with a question and sixteen lines of points, made from right to
    left without counting, the mind held on the matter asked. Everything else follows by rule.
  </p>

  <h2>1. The sixteen lines and the four Mothers</h2>
  <p>
    Mark sixteen rows of points. Count each row: an odd number yields one point, an even number
    two. Rows 1–4 give the first <em>Mother</em>, rows 5–8 the second, and so on: four figures of
    four lines each. Agrippa describes the operation:
  </p>
  <Quote id="agrippa/general/casting-mothers" compact />
  <p>Gerard of Cremona adds the traditional cautions about when not to ask:</p>
  <Quote id="gerard/casting-caution" compact />

  <h2>2. Daughters, Nieces, Witnesses, Judge</h2>
  <p>
    The four <em>Daughters</em> are made by reading the Mothers sideways: the first Daughter takes
    the head-lines of Mothers I–IV in order, the second their neck-lines, and so on. The four
    <em>Nieces</em> are made by adding neighbouring pairs line by line: odd sums give one point,
    even sums two. The two <em>Witnesses</em> are added from the Nieces in the same way, and the
    <em>Judge</em> from the Witnesses.
  </p>
  <Quote id="agrippa/general/casting-daughters" compact />

  <h2>The shield chart</h2>
  <ShieldChart />

  <h2>3. Into the houses</h2>
  <p>
    For judgment the first twelve figures are also placed in the twelve astrological houses. The
    common way, which Agrippa reports first, sets the Mothers in houses 1–4, the Daughters in
    5–8 and the Nieces in 9–12, in order, as the figure below shows:
  </p>
  <HouseChart />
  <p>
    Agrippa then gives his own “astrological” arrangement, and other authors differ again:
    Crowley's Golden Dawn scheme begins with the first Mother in the tenth house. See
    <a href={withBase('/library/agrippa/of-geomancy/')}>Agrippa's text</a> and
    <a href={withBase('/library/crowley/twelve-houses/')}>Crowley's chapter III</a> for the variants.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Judgment</h2>
  <p>
    If the Judge is good, the matter ends well; the Witnesses qualify it; the figure in the house
    of the question, its aspects, dignities and springings refine the answer. One warning is
    universal in the Golden Dawn line:
  </p>
  <Quote id="crowley/techniques/destroy-rule" compact />
  <p>Continue with <a href={withBase('/techniques/')}>the techniques of judgment →</a></p>
</Prose>
